ir is bad so we should exercise indoors.</p><p> Personally, I don't think there is much we can do as individuals. We can't stop producing waste water and rubbish every day. We can  reduce it, but we can't avoid it completely.  I think the government must take the lead.</p><p>I recently bought my first car. It's a Mitsubishi Lancer, which has good fuel efficiency. I use it to take my daughter to school and so that we can all get out of the city at the weekend and go somewhere where the  environment is a bit better. There is a Chinese expression: if you want to correct others, you should first correct yourself. That applies to the west's criticism of our country's environmental record. Global warming is not  a problem for one person, or one country. It is a problem for humanity as a whole. All countries must make a contribution.</p><p>It's hard to know what I can do as an individual. If our government takes the initiative and sets new regulations, I will follow them.  I guess most people are like that.</p><h2>Xu Zebin, 42,  manager at a foreign oil company </h2><p>I think I am doing very well living an environmentally friendly lifestyle because I always use buses for commuting. I think that is the best thing I can do to reduce emissions. It is part of my job because  I am working on a project for sustainable   urban mobility.</p><p>I have never had a car because public  transport in Beijing is quite good. It is sometimes a little crowded, as in any country, but that is not a big issue. Personal convenience does not justify emissions.</p><p>At least once a week, I get out of the city and walk around Fragrant Hills in the west. The air there is pretty good. But when you look back at the city from afar, you notice how bad the pollution is.</p><p>I do some recycling, mostly of plastic bags from the supermarket which I use for rubbish. To be honest, I haven't done anything to make my life carbon neutral. Even though I work in the environmental field, the concept is hard for me to understand. And if we can't understand, how can we take action?</p><p>Global warming worries me, but I think the best way for China to contribute to a solution is to promote energy efficiency. It is a practical, visible step. People can feel the result in their day-to-day lives. It is a fact that China is going to be the biggest emitter of greenhouse gases. But no one country can solve the problem. The responsibility is global.</p><p>I wish schools would do more to educate people about the environment. I have a 17-year-old son, but I have never heard him talk about these issues at home. But overall, awareness is improving among the public and officials.</p><h2>Sun Jie, 29, magazine editor</h2><p>I do what I can to be green. In my office,  I encourage staff to bring their own cups rather than using the paper ones by the  office cooler. We also have a cotton \"office bag\" that we use when buying snacks so that we don't need plastic bags. If I go shopping with my friends, I tell them not to use them  as well. But I don't carry my own chopsticks around yet.</p><p>To be honest, I don't think about the  environment when I am shopping. I try to buy locally made goods to help the local market.  I also avoid goods in fancy packages - it's  better to buy fruit loose.  But I don't separate my rubbish. The main reason is that the  garbage bins don't show you how to do it.</p><p>To China's critics in the west, I would say, don't just complain, share your technology with us. China is the factory of the world. We make all the Christmas trees and the gifts that go under them for the developed countries. They want more so we make more. In the US, they don't want pollution so they close their factories and move them here. They are happy to buy the cheap goods we make. But then they come back and blame us for pollution  because there are so many factories here.</p><h2>Huang Weizhen, 28, Greenpeace campaigner</h2><p>My biggest worry is the air pollution in Beijing. The weather is usually bad, we don't get much sunshine and the air we breathe is not good, so I try to avoid spending too much time on the street. I either stay indoors or go quickly to the nearest public transport.</p><p>The problem has been caused by the  emergence in China of a middle class. More and more people are buying cars, but the  government has relaxed controls on car usage, so the air quality is getting worse. I have a bicycle but usually I travel by subway. I think people should avoid using private cars unless they are visiting friends who live far away. In daily life, they should use bikes or public transport. </p><p>I avoid using plastic bags because they don't decompose easily. I take my own chopsticks everywhere so I can avoid using disposable ones. At home, I use energy-saving light bulbs and I try to buy environmentally friendly clothing, such as cotton that is white, grey or black. It is better not to have things with bright colours because they are made with toxic  synthetic dyes. There is a line of environmentally friendly T-shirts on sale here, but at the moment they are a little too expensive for me.</p><p>I buy organic food bought locally as well as environmentally friendly DIY materials. There is not much I can do about energy efficiency in my home because the central heating is  controlled by the government, not me.</p><h2>Yuan Fengli, 25, photographer</h2><p>I have just bought a car and, yes, it contributes to the pollution. It is a bad thing for the environment, but living in the modern world you have to live with that.  I really wanted a car and now I have one. Since I got it, I haven't taken a single bus. I sometimes use taxis. But my car's engine isn't too big - just 1.6 litres. I try to save fuel with the way I drive, by not using the brake too often. </p><p>I also try to help the environment by  not throwing away batteries. I tried to use rechargeable ones for my work, but they don't work well with the camera's flash so I just buy regular AAs. I keep hold of them, even though I haven't worked out what to do with them yet. My girlfriend calls me an idiot for doing this, but I don't want them to cause pollution. I also try to make full use of plastic bags by using them for garbage or for picking up after my dog.</p><p>Of course, I don't do enough. If I earned enough money I would be happy to donate money to organisations that work to help the environment. But mostly I don't think about the environment that much.</p><p>When you develop as a country like we have, you have a phase when you build a lot a factories and that creates a lot of pollution. Only later do you realise this problem and  do something about it. I think China is  50-100 years behind the west. I think the  government realises this and is doing something to help, but I also understand if they don't do much because they have to drive  the economy forward.</p><h2>Fu Leiyun, 26  shop assistant</h2><p>I don't do much for the environment, but I make an effort. When I go shopping, I always take my own cotton bag. I have been doing that for three and a half years since I saw a television programme about how hard it is for plastic to biodegrade. </p><p>I have a car that my parents bought for me. I try not to use it for short distances. Instead,  I take a bus or walk. I sort my rubbish into  recycleable and non-recycleable bags. I don't drop litter, but if I see my friends doing that I help them pick it up.</p><p>We have too much traffic and not enough trees. In other countries, I think cities are much greener than ours. </p><p>But I am a common person. I have no power to decide anything and no special knowledge. All I can do is save energy in my daily life and encourage my friends to do the same.</p><p><strong>&#183; </strong>Post questions and answers to <strong>Ask Leo</strong> The Guardian, 119 Farringdon Road, London EC1 3ER <strong>Fax: 020-7713 4366</strong>. Email: <a href=\"mailto:ethical.living@guardian.co.uk\">ethical.living@guardian.co.uk</a> Please include your address and telephone number</p>","headline":"'You buy our cheap goods. Don't blame us'","trailText":"<p>China is often branded the planet's worst polluter. <strong>Jonathan Watts</strong> asks some of Beijing's citizens how they are trying to do their bit for the environment - and how they view their 'dirty man' tag</p>","newspaperPageNumber":"18","shouldHideAdverts":"false","publication":"The Guardian","showInRelatedContent":"true","shortUrl":"http://gu.com/p/x2zk8","wordcount":"1606","commentable":"false","internalContentCode":"332312783","allowUgc":"false","isPremoderated":"false","byline":"Jonathan Watts","newspaperEditionDate":"2008-01-31T00:00:00Z","internalPageCode":"588851","productionOffice":"UK","liveBloggingNow":"false"},"webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/environment/2008/jan/31/ethicalliving.waste","apiUrl":"http://beta.content.guardianapis.com/environment/2008/jan/31/ethicalliving.waste","tags":[{"id":"environment/ethical-living","webTitle":"Ethical and green living","description":"Tips on ethical and green living","type":"keyword","sectionId":"environment","sectionName":"Environment","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/environment/ethical-living","apiUrl":"http://beta.content.guardianapis.com/environment/ethical-living","references":[]},{"id":"environment/plasticbags","webTitle":"Plastic bags","type":"keyword","sectionId":"environment","sectionName":"Environment","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/environment/plasticbags","apiUrl":"http://beta.content.guardianapis.com/environment/plasticbags","references":[]},{"id":"environment/waste","webTitle":"Waste","type":"keyword","sectionId":"environment","sectionName":"Environment","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/environment/waste","apiUrl":"http://beta.content.guardianapis.com/environment/waste","references":[]},{"id":"environment/pollution","webTitle":"Pollution","type":"keyword","sectionId":"environment","sectionName":"Environment","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/envi