2","webTitle":"G2","type":"newspaper-book","sectionId":"theguardian","sectionName":"From the Guardian","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/theguardian/g2","apiUrl":"http://beta.content.guardianapis.com/theguardian/g2","references":[]},{"id":"environment/carbon-emissions","webTitle":"Greenhouse gas emissions","type":"keyword","sectionId":"environment","sectionName":"Environment","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/environment/carbon-emissions","apiUrl":"http://beta.content.guardianapis.com/environment/carbon-emissions","references":[]},{"id":"publication/theguardian","webTitle":"The Guardian","type":"publication","sectionId":"theguardian","sectionName":"From the Guardian","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/theguardian/all","apiUrl":"http://beta.content.guardianapis.com/publication/theguardian","references":[]},{"id":"world/asia-pacific","webTitle":"Asia Pacific","type":"keyword","sectionId":"world","sectionName":"World news","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/world/asia-pacific","apiUrl":"http://beta.content.guardianapis.com/world/asia-pacific","references":[]},{"id":"type/article","webTitle":"Article","type":"type","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/articles","apiUrl":"http://beta.content.guardianapis.com/type/article","references":[]}],"references":[],"elements":[]},{"webTitle":"Letters: Carbon capture's role in a sustainable future","webPublicationDate":"2009-08-17T23:05:20Z","sectionName":"Environment","sectionId":"environment","id":"environment/2009/aug/18/green-carbon-capture-offset","fields":{"hasStoryPackage":"false","lastModified":"2014-06-11T14:20:51Z","strap":"Letters","body":"<p>Regarding your <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/environment/2009/aug/13/coal-stations-activism\" title=\"interview with Sustainable Development Commission Chair Will Day\">interview with Sustainable Development Commission chairman Will Day</a> (Report, 14 August), I feel I must point out the importance and urgency of developing carbon capture and storage technology (CCS). With world demand for coal set to increase by over 60% over the period 2006-30, according to the <a href=\"http://www.iea.org/\" title=\"International Energy Agency\">International Energy Agency</a>, as countries like China and India build the new power stations they need, it is clear that there is no credible solution to climate change without CCS.</p><p>Day asks to be shown where CCS is working, and that is the right question to ask. CCS needs to be demonstrated on a large scale in a power station, and the UK is taking a global lead in driving the technology to this next stage. We have already launched one competition for a 300MW demonstration and plan to support up to a further three in the UK. We  also want any new coal-fired power station constructed in the UK to demonstrate CCS on a substantial proportion of its capacity â reducing emissions from day one of operation and making a real contribution to the development of CCS.</p><p>With regard to the planned expansion of Heathrow, we have always said that the expansion cannot proceed unless stringent environmental limits on noise and air quality are met. In addition, aviation emissions will be capped under the <a href=\"http://ec.europa.eu/environment/climat/emission/index_en.htm\" title=\"EU emissions trading system\">EU emissions trading system</a> and the government has sent a strong signal to the air transport industry by announcing a new target to reduce CO<sub>2</sub> emissions from UK aviation to below 2005 levels by 2050.</p><p><strong>David Kidney</strong></p><p><em>Undersecretary of state for the</em><a href=\"http://www.decc.gov.uk/\" title=\" Department of Energy and Climate Change\"><em> Department of Energy and Climate Change</em></a></p><p></p><p>â¢ The chairman of the Sustainable Development Commission is right that statistics like \"one [coal power station] a week opening in China\" can't be waved as some trump card to justify doing nothing on climate change. But they are a reality check.</p><p>On air travel, also discussed, the Chinese are restricting themselves to a mere new airport a month. This brings UK aviation and its 0.1% share of all global emissions into rather stark relief. Avoiding Heathrow's acute capacity problems and third runway won't dent the problem; and discouraging certain types of flying rapidly becomes a moral maze. The answer is Day's remedy: pricing-in carbon. This is the way to change behaviour and accelerate innovation.</p><p><strong>Robert Siddall</strong></p><p><a href=\"http://www.aoa.org.uk/home/index.asp\" title=\"Airport Operators Association\"><em>Airport Operators Association</em></a><em> </em>&nbsp;</p><p></p><p>â¢ Will Day is right to call for the price of air travel to rise and for the planned third runway at Heathrow not to go ahead. As well as emitting carbon dioxide, planes also contribute to global warming by emitting nitrogen oxide and water vapour at high altitudes. Estimates vary, but total global warming caused by air travel is probably at least twice as bad as burning the same amount of oil in other ways.</p><p>However, the argument about building coal-fired power stations in the UK is less straightforward. Regardless of what Britain does, China, India and many other countries will be massively expanding this form of power generation, and if their power stations are not fitted with very effective carbon capture and storage  technology, they will have a devastating impact upon the climate. Therefore, it may make sense for the UK to build some coal-fired power stations, but only if they are used to develop CCS. CCS needs to be greater than 90% efficient, and it needs to be cheap enough to be used worldwide, probably with subsidy from the EU and the US.</p><p><strong>Richard Mountford</strong></p><p><a href=\"http://www.twopercentfortheplanet.org/\" title=\"www.twopercentfortheplanet.org \"><em>www.twopercentfortheplanet.org </em></a></p><p></p><p>â¢ You are right to highlight the need for <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/business/2009/aug/16/carbon-capture-gas-power-generation\" title=\"carbon capture and storage technology to be fitted to all kinds of fossil fuel power stations in the future\">carbon capture and storage technology to be fitted to all kinds of fossil fuel power stations in the future</a>. Many believe that CCS should just be fitted to ongoing and proposed coal-fired power plants but this would dangerously distort the market against cheaper coal and in favour of more import-dependent gas-fired power stations, on which the UK is becoming dangerously overreliant. Electricity from coal is cheaper than that generated by gas. The gas price is tied to a fluctuating oil price. It is accepted that CCS on coal plants will increase costs, but there is no policy consistency in only making one fossil fuel pay the price.</p><p>Importantly, 90% of all ongoing and approved power station construction in the UK today is gas-fired; but this point was not highlighted in the latest energy white paper, nor was the huge \"dash for gas\" which has taken place since 1997.</p><p>The government should now be looking to support new technologies which allow us to clean up, modernise and maintain our ongoing coal-fired stations before we can install CCS. New pre- and post-combustion coal stations must also be approved alongside better energy storage technologies for intermittent renewables. In order to help maintain some balance, the EU large combustion plant directive, which rules we must close many of our coal- and oil-fired power stations within six years, must also be re-examined.</p><p><strong>Tony Lodge</strong></p><p><em>Centre for Policy Studies</em></p><p></p><p><em>â¢ </em>Further to your report (<a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/environment/2009/aug/12/vestas-factory-closes-despite-campaign\" title=\"Vestas factory closes despite campaign\">Vestas factory closes despite campaign</a>, 12 August), the campaign to save the only major wind turbine blade manufacturer in the UK remains an urgent cause. Why? Because the fundamental issues have not changed: the decision to stop making wind turbine blades does undermine the government's promise of a \"green revolution\" that would usher in more renewable energy production and green jobs.</p><p>One of the questions that we all â campaigners, both environmental and trade union, and all working people â need to examine is whether we can let job creation, and the transition to renewable energy production, rest on the short-term business decisions of private companies whose guiding principle is their bottom line. We argue that we cannot.</p><p><strong>Edward Maltby</strong></p><p><a href=\"http://workersclimateaction.co.uk/\" title=\"Workers' Climate Action\"><em>Workers' Climate Action</em></a></p>","headline":"Carbon capture's role in a sustainable future","trailText":"<strong>Letters: </strong>I must point out the importance and urgency of developing carbon capture and storage technology","newspaperPageNumber":"33","shouldHideAdverts":"false","publication":"The Guardian","showInRelatedContent":"true","shortUrl":"http://gu.com/p/2a565","wordcount":"932","commentable":"false","internalContentCode":"351741280","allowUgc":"false","internalOctopusCode":"2350812","isPremoderated":"false","newspaperEditionDate":"2009-08-18T00:00:00Z","internalPageCode":"1263524","productionOffice":"UK","liveBloggingNow":"false","commentCloseDate":"2009-08-20T23:05:20Z"},"webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/environment/2009/aug/18/green-carbon-capture-offset","apiUrl":"http://beta.content.guardianapis.com/environment/2009/aug/18/green-carbon-capture-offset","tags":[{"id":"environment/environment","webTitle":"Environment","type":"keyword","sectionId":"environment","sectionName":"Environment","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/environment/environment","apiUrl":"http://beta.content.guardianapis.com/environment/environment","references":[]},{"id":"environment/carbon-capture-and-storage","webTitle":"Carbon 